One mole = 6.022 × 10²³ particles (Avogadro's Number, NA). It is the amount of substance containing as many
elementary entities as atoms in exactly 12 g of Carbon-12. Molar Mass = mass in grams of one mole
(numerically equal to atomic/molecular weight).
Quantity Formula Example
Number of moles (n) n = mass / molar mass 36 g HnO ® n = 36/18 = 2 mol
Number of particles N = n × Nn 2 mol HnO ® 12.04 × 10²³ molecules
Molarity (M) M = moles / volume(L) 0.5 mol NaCl in 1 L = 0.5 M
Molality (m) m = moles / kg(solvent) Independent of temperature
Normality (N) N = equivalents / L Used in acid-base & redox titrations
Mole Fraction (c) cn = nn / (nn + n_b) Used in gas law partial pressures
2.2 Balancing Chemical Equations
Chemical equations must be balanced to satisfy the Law of Conservation of Mass: atoms of each element
must be equal on both sides.
Worked Example – Combustion of Methane
Unbalanced: CHn + On ® COn + HnO
Balanced: CHn + 2On ® COn + 2HnO
Molar ratio: 1 mol CHn requires 2 mol On; produces 1 mol COn + 2 mol HnO
Environmental use: Calculate COn emissions from burning 1 tonne of natural gas.
2.3 Limiting Reagent & Percentage Yield
The limiting reagent is the reactant that is completely consumed first, determining the maximum amount of
product. The excess reagent is left over. Percentage Yield = (Actual Yield / Theoretical Yield) × 100.
Environmental significance: In water treatment, when adding excess lime Ca(OH)n for phosphorus removal, knowing the
limiting reagent prevents both under-dosing (treatment failure) and over-dosing (cost and pH problems).
