3. Gibbs' Free Energy
Gibbs' Free Energy (G) combines enthalpy (heat content) and entropy (disorder) to predict whether a chemical
reaction will occur spontaneously under constant temperature and pressure conditions. Named after J. Willard
Gibbs (1878).
3.1 The Fundamental Equation
Gibbs' Energy Equation
DG = DH – TDS
Where:
• DG = Change in Gibbs Free Energy (kJ/mol)
• DH = Change in Enthalpy (heat absorbed/released, kJ/mol)
• T = Absolute Temperature in Kelvin (K)
• DS = Change in Entropy (J/mol·K) – measure of disorder
3.2 Spontaneity Rules
DH DS DG Spontaneous? Example
- + Always - YES (all T) Combustion reactions
+ - Always + NEVER Decomposition of water (electrolysis needed)
- - - at low T Only at low T Freezing of water (0°C)
+ + - at high T Only at high T Melting of ice (>0°C)
3.3 Relationship with Equilibrium Constant
At equilibrium, DG = 0. The Standard Gibbs Energy (DG°) is related to the equilibrium constant by: DG° = -RT
ln K, where R = 8.314 J/mol·K and K is the equilibrium constant. A large negative DG° means K >> 1 (products
favoured). A large positive DG° means K << 1 (reactants favoured).
