4. Chemical Potential
Chemical Potential (μ) is the partial molar Gibbs free energy: the change in total Gibbs energy of a system
when one mole of a substance is added, while T, P, and amounts of other components remain constant. It is the
driving force for chemical reactions and mass transfer.
Formula: μn = μn° + RT ln(an)
where μn° = standard chemical potential, an = activity of species i (» concentration for dilute solutions, partial
pressure for gases), R = gas constant, T = temperature.
Key Principles:
• Substances move from regions of HIGH chemical potential to LOW (like water flows downhill).
• At equilibrium: μ(reactants) = μ(products) for all species.
• For ideal gases: μ = μ° + RT ln(P/P°) where P is partial pressure.
• For ideal solutions: μ = μ° + RT ln(c) where c is mole fraction.
Environmental Application How Chemical Potential Is Used
Pollutant partitioning Predicts distribution of pollutant between air-water-soil phases
Osmosis in cells Water moves to higher chemical potential (lower water activity)
Ion exchange in soil Ions migrate to equalise chemical potential across soil-water interface
Evaporation of VOCs VOC moves from soil (high μ) to air (low μ) until equilibrium
Membrane processes RO/UF driven by chemical potential difference across membrane
