5. Chemical Kinetics
Chemical Kinetics studies the rate of chemical reactions and the factors controlling them (concentration,
temperature, catalysts, surface area, light). While thermodynamics tells us IF a reaction will occur, kinetics tells
us HOW FAST.
5.1 Rate of Reaction
Rate = decrease in concentration of reactant (or increase in product) per unit time. Units: mol Ln¹ sn¹. For
reaction A ® B: Rate = -d[A]/dt = +d[B]/dt
5.2 Rate Law and Order of Reaction
For reaction: aA + bB ® products, the rate law is: Rate = k[A]n[B]n
Order Rate Law Half-life (t½) Units of k Example
0 Rate = k t½ = [A]n/2k mol Ln¹ sn¹ Enzyme saturation reactions
1 Rate = k[A] t½ = 0.693/k sn¹ Radioactive decay, first-order pollutant degradation
2 Rate = k[A]² t½ = 1/(k[A]n) L moln¹ sn¹ NOn dimerisation, ozone reactions
5.3 Arrhenius Equation – Effect of Temperature
Arrhenius Equation
k = A × e^(-En/RT) OR ln k = ln A - En/RT
where: k = rate constant; A = frequency/pre-exponential factor; En = activation energy (kJ/mol); R = 8.314
J/mol·K; T = temperature (K)
Practical rule: Rate » doubles for every 10°C rise (for En ~ 50 kJ/mol)
