6. Chemical Equilibria
A system reaches chemical equilibrium when the forward and reverse reaction rates are equal and
concentrations remain constant (though reactions continue). Equilibrium is dynamic, not static.
6.1 Equilibrium Constant
For reaction: aA + bB n cC + dD
Equilibrium Expressions
Kc = [C]n[D]n / [A]n[B]n (concentration; mol/L)
Kp = (Pn_C × Pn_D) / (Pn_A × Pn_B) (partial pressures; atm)
Relationship: Kp = Kc(RT)^Dn where Dn = moles of gas (products - reactants)
K >> 1: Products favoured (complete reaction) | K << 1: Reactants favoured | K = 1: Roughly equal
6.2 Le Chatelier's Principle
When a system at equilibrium is disturbed, it shifts to counteract the disturbance and re-establish equilibrium.
Disturbance System Response Environmental Example
Increase [reactant] Shifts forward ® more product Adding lime shifts carbonate equilibrium
Decrease [product] Shifts forward Precipitation removes Ca²n ® more CaCOn dissolves
Increase temperature Favours endothermic direction Warmer water holds less COn (exothermic dissolution)
Increase pressure Favours fewer moles of gas High pressure COn storage in oceans
Add catalyst No shift; equilibrium reached
faster
Enzyme treatment speeds biodegradation
