7. Solubility of Gases in Water – Henry's Law
The dissolution of gases in water is fundamental to aquatic chemistry, oxygen availability for aquatic life, COn
cycling, and environmental fate of pollutants. Henry's Law (William Henry, 1803) quantifies this.
Henry's Law
p = Kn × C OR C = p / Kn
where: p = partial pressure of gas (atm); C = molar concentration in solution (mol/L); Kn = Henry's law
constant (atm·L/mol) – specific to each gas and temperature.
Higher Kn ® gas less soluble in water (e.g., On, Nn have high Kn)
